  "style": "",
  "texts": [
    "Given a question x and its set of corresponding rubrics R x = {(r x,k, w x,k)} K k=1, where each r x,k is a rubric (item) and w x,k is its corresponding weight, we assess the quality of the response y with the rubric-based scoring function",
    "where, for each rubric r x,k, we use a separate judge LM that returns 0, 0.5, or 1 depending on the extent to which r x,k is satisfied by the final answer in y.",
    "We compute this rubric score using only the final answer, i.e., regardless of the reasoning and search traces.",
    "Note that rubrics are instance-specific, i.e., each question has its own set of rubrics.",
    "Rubric weights can be negative to penalize undesirable aspects."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}